# DiaHealth 360 — Cursor Project Rules

You are helping build DiaHealth 360, a clinical command center web app for a
diabetes care cohort, backed by a read-only Synthea FHIR medallion-gold SQLite
warehouse. Follow these rules on EVERY request.

## Stack (do not change without being asked)
- Backend: Python 3 + Flask. A small app factory in `backend/`, route blueprints
  in `backend/routes/`.
- Frontend: plain HTML + CSS + vanilla JS (no framework, no build step). Scripts
  load in dependency order via <script> tags.
- Database: SQLite at `data/diahealth_compact_full.db`. Served read-only.
- This mirrors a previously-proven prototype — keep it simple, do not introduce
  React/Vue/bundlers/ORMs unless explicitly asked.

## Environment
- ALWAYS use `python3` and `pip3`, never bare `python` / `pip`.
- Use a virtual environment (`venv/`). Activate before running.
- The app serves the frontend itself; open http://localhost:5000 (or 5050 if 5000
  is taken — macOS AirPlay uses 5000).

## THE SCHEMA RULE (most important)
The UI layout is driven by the database SCHEMA, not by one patient's rows.
- A panel BELONGS if a gold table/column can ever feed it — even when a given
  patient has zero rows (then show an honest empty state like
  "No known allergies recorded").
- NEVER build panels for data that has NO schema at all. These do not exist and
  must never be fabricated:
  - CGM / continuous glucose / Time-in-Range / AGP / GMI / glucose variability /
    glucose heatmap
  - medication adherence percentages
  - composite "Health Score" or "Diabetes Control Score" gauges
  - lifestyle / wearable metrics (steps, sleep, stress, calories, hydration)
  - hypoglycemia-event counts
- If asked to build any of the above, refuse and explain there is no data source;
  offer the schema-backed alternative instead.
- NEVER invent values, patients, drug names, specialties, or procedures that are
  not in the database. If unsure whether something exists, query the DB first.

## Data honesty (known dataset facts — state these, don't hide them)
- Synthetic Synthea data. HbA1c skews low (cohort avg ~4%); do not "correct" it.
- Provider specialty is uniform ("General Practice Physician"). Do not invent
  endocrinologists/nephrologists/dietitians.
- Payer/insurance is a placeholder — show "Not recorded".
- ~28% of medication rows have codes outside the med reference set (null
  medication) — handle gracefully.
- Allergies are sparse (19 records across 25 patients) — empty states are normal.
- Use `gold_fact_medication` (compat, code-keyed) for medication display queries;
  `gold_fact_medication_request` / `_admin` are the richer modern tables.

## Database safety
- Open the warehouse READ-ONLY (sqlite `mode=ro`). Never write to it.
- Only SELECT / WITH queries against the warehouse. Reject anything else.
- Resolve dates via `gold_dim_date` (date_key is yyyymmdd). Join codes via
  `gold_dim_code`. Patient surrogate key is `patient_key`; FHIR id is `patient_id`.

## Working style
- Build ONE screen at a time, end to end, and verify it loads with real data
  before moving on. Do not scaffold all 17 screens at once.
- After a screen works, suggest a git commit.
- Keep functions small; keep the data layer in one place so the same metric
  reads the same value on every screen (single source of truth).
- When given a mock screen image, match its layout, but drop any no-schema panel
  per THE SCHEMA RULE and replace with a schema-backed panel or honest empty state.

## The 17 navigation screens (one per nav item)
Overview, Patient 360, Timeline, Trends & Analytics, Labs, Medications,
Encounters, Procedures, Immunizations, Allergies, Documents, Reports, Devices,
Care Team, Complications, Care Gaps, Settings.
See CONTEXT.md for which gold tables back each screen.
